[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":427},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fdocker\u002F2023\u002F01\u002F22\u002Fstep-by-step-docker-dockerfile\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fdocker\u002F2023\u002F01\u002F22\u002Fstep-by-step-docker-dockerfile\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fdocker\u002F2023\u002F01\u002F22\u002Fstep-by-step-docker-dockerfile\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fdocker\u002F2023\u002F01\u002F22\u002Fstep-by-step-docker-dockerfile\u002F":403,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fdocker\u002F2023\u002F01\u002F22\u002Fstep-by-step-docker-dockerfile\u002F":412},"\u002Fdocker\u002F20230122\u002F3483968861\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":384,"date":385,"description":386,"extension":387,"lang":388,"meta":389,"navigation":390,"path":391,"readingMinutes":392,"seo":393,"standalone":394,"stem":395,"tags":396,"tldr":399,"updated":400,"url":401,"__hash__":402},"content\u002Fen\u002FDocker\u002Fstep-by-step-docker-dockerfile.md","(2) Step-by-Step Docker — Dockerfile","4485663954",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":369},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,31,34,39,46,49,65,68,72,79,88,93,109,115,124,127,142,153,156,165,168,172,194,203,207,210,219,229,245,249,255,264,267,282,290,294,307,316,320,323,332,338,342,348,357,362,365],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Picking up the second half of the last post — let's talk about the Dockerfile.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"what-is-a-dockerfile","What is a Dockerfile?",[17,25,26],{},"A Dockerfile is essentially a script file. It tells Docker what to do in order to build a Docker Image. To know what Docker's doing, you need to understand the commands you'll see inside.",[12,28,30],{"id":29},"dockerfile-commands","Dockerfile commands",[17,32,33],{},"Let's walk through the common commands.",[35,36,38],"h3",{"id":37},"from","FROM",[17,40,41,42,45],{},"Tells Docker which Image to use as the base. Since an Image is a kind of disk image (we covered that last post), ",[43,44,38],"code",{}," is just saying \"use this image as the starting point\".",[17,47,48],{},"For example, to use Node.js 16.15.0:",[50,51,56],"pre",{"className":52,"code":53,"language":54,"meta":55,"style":55},"language-dockerfile shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","FROM node:16.15.0\n","dockerfile","",[43,57,58],{"__ignoreMap":55},[59,60,63],"span",{"class":61,"line":62},"line",1,[59,64,53],{},[17,66,67],{},"Docker now provisions the environment with Node.js 16.15.0.",[35,69,71],{"id":70},"run","RUN",[17,73,74,75,78],{},"Dead simple — tells Docker to run a command. If you're on Node.js and you want to run ",[43,76,77],{},"app.js",":",[50,80,82],{"className":52,"code":81,"language":54,"meta":55,"style":55},"RUN node app.js\n",[43,83,84],{"__ignoreMap":55},[59,85,86],{"class":61,"line":62},[59,87,81],{},[17,89,90,92],{},[43,91,71],{}," is just like typing into your terminal, except inside Docker. For multiple commands:",[50,94,96],{"className":52,"code":95,"language":54,"meta":55,"style":55},"RUN npm install\nRUN npm run build\n",[43,97,98,103],{"__ignoreMap":55},[59,99,100],{"class":61,"line":62},[59,101,102],{},"RUN npm install\n",[59,104,106],{"class":61,"line":105},2,[59,107,108],{},"RUN npm run build\n",[17,110,111,112,78],{},"Easy. Just note one command per line. If you want to combine commands, chain with ",[43,113,114],{},"&&",[50,116,118],{"className":52,"code":117,"language":54,"meta":55,"style":55},"RUN npm install && npm run build\n",[43,119,120],{"__ignoreMap":55},[59,121,122],{"class":61,"line":62},[59,123,117],{},[17,125,126],{},"You might also see the array form:",[50,128,130],{"className":52,"code":129,"language":54,"meta":55,"style":55},"RUN [\"npm\", \"install\"]\nRUN [\"npm\", \"run\", \"build\"]\n",[43,131,132,137],{"__ignoreMap":55},[59,133,134],{"class":61,"line":62},[59,135,136],{},"RUN [\"npm\", \"install\"]\n",[59,138,139],{"class":61,"line":105},[59,140,141],{},"RUN [\"npm\", \"run\", \"build\"]\n",[17,143,144,145,148,149,152],{},"This is equivalent to ",[43,146,147],{},"npm install"," and ",[43,150,151],{},"npm run build",". The benefit of the array form is that it avoids issues when arguments contain spaces.",[17,154,155],{},"If you want to chain multiple commands using array form:",[50,157,159],{"className":52,"code":158,"language":54,"meta":55,"style":55},"RUN [\"npm\", \"install\", \"&&\", \"npm\", \"run\", \"build\"]\n",[43,160,161],{"__ignoreMap":55},[59,162,163],{"class":61,"line":62},[59,164,158],{},[17,166,167],{},"Starting to make sense?",[35,169,171],{"id":170},"cmd","CMD",[17,173,174,176,177,179,180,182,183,187,188,182,190,193],{},[43,175,171],{}," is similar to ",[43,178,71],{},", but with a key difference — ",[43,181,171],{}," runs ",[184,185,186],"strong",{},"when the Container starts",", while ",[43,189,71],{},[184,191,192],{},"when the Image is being built",". Different lifecycle phases.",[17,195,196,197,199,200,202],{},"This one's a bit subtle. The mental model: a Dockerfile runs line by line, and after the whole thing finishes, the result is packaged into an Image. ",[43,198,71],{}," executes during the build (Image creation), while ",[43,201,171],{}," executes only when you actually start a Container from that Image.",[35,204,206],{"id":205},"copy","COPY",[17,208,209],{},"Pretty straightforward — copy a file. To copy a file into the Docker environment:",[50,211,213],{"className":52,"code":212,"language":54,"meta":55,"style":55},"COPY .\u002Fapp.js \u002Fapp\u002Fapp.js\n",[43,214,215],{"__ignoreMap":55},[59,216,217],{"class":61,"line":62},[59,218,212],{},[17,220,221,222,224,225,228],{},"This copies ",[43,223,77],{}," to ",[43,226,227],{},"\u002Fapp\u002Fapp.js"," inside the Docker environment.",[17,230,231,232,235,236,241,242,244],{},"You might see a similar command called ",[43,233,234],{},"ADD",". Docker's official recommendation is to ",[184,237,238,239],{},"avoid ",[43,240,234],{}," in favor of ",[43,243,206],{},".",[35,246,248],{"id":247},"env","ENV",[17,250,251,252,78],{},"You'll use this one a lot — sets environment variables. To set ",[43,253,254],{},"NODE_ENV",[50,256,258],{"className":52,"code":257,"language":54,"meta":55,"style":55},"ENV NODE_ENV production\n",[43,259,260],{"__ignoreMap":55},[59,261,262],{"class":61,"line":62},[59,263,257],{},[17,265,266],{},"Multiple ENVs:",[50,268,270],{"className":52,"code":269,"language":54,"meta":55,"style":55},"ENV NODE_ENV production \\\n    PORT 3000\n",[43,271,272,277],{"__ignoreMap":55},[59,273,274],{"class":61,"line":62},[59,275,276],{},"ENV NODE_ENV production \\\n",[59,278,279],{"class":61,"line":105},[59,280,281],{},"    PORT 3000\n",[17,283,284,285,148,287,244],{},"That sets both ",[43,286,254],{},[43,288,289],{},"PORT",[35,291,293],{"id":292},"arg","ARG",[17,295,296,176,298,300,301,303,304,306],{},[43,297,293],{},[43,299,248],{},", but they run in different phases. ",[43,302,293],{}," is available during the Image build, while ",[43,305,248],{}," is available when the Container starts.",[17,308,309,310,312,313,315],{},"Mental model: like global vs local variables. ",[43,311,293],{}," is global (build-time), ",[43,314,248],{}," is local (runtime).",[35,317,319],{"id":318},"expose","EXPOSE",[17,321,322],{},"Also common — tells Docker which port the container uses. To use port 3000:",[50,324,326],{"className":52,"code":325,"language":54,"meta":55,"style":55},"EXPOSE 3000\n",[43,327,328],{"__ignoreMap":55},[59,329,330],{"class":61,"line":62},[59,331,325],{},[17,333,334,335,337],{},"Why ",[43,336,319],{},"? Because without it, Docker doesn't know which port the container intends to use, which causes issues down the line.",[35,339,341],{"id":340},"workdir","WORKDIR",[17,343,344,345,78],{},"Sets the working directory. To set it to ",[43,346,347],{},"\u002Fapp",[50,349,351],{"className":52,"code":350,"language":54,"meta":55,"style":55},"WORKDIR \u002Fapp\n",[43,352,353],{"__ignoreMap":55},[59,354,355],{"class":61,"line":62},[59,356,350],{},[17,358,359,360,244],{},"All subsequent commands run inside ",[43,361,347],{},[17,363,364],{},"These are the commands you'll see most often. There are others, but this is enough for now.",[366,367,368],"style",{},"html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}",{"title":55,"searchDepth":105,"depth":105,"links":370},[371,372,373],{"id":14,"depth":105,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":105,"text":23},{"id":29,"depth":105,"text":30,"children":374},[375,377,378,379,380,381,382,383],{"id":37,"depth":376,"text":38},3,{"id":70,"depth":376,"text":71},{"id":170,"depth":376,"text":171},{"id":205,"depth":376,"text":206},{"id":247,"depth":376,"text":248},{"id":292,"depth":376,"text":293},{"id":318,"depth":376,"text":319},{"id":340,"depth":376,"text":341},"Docker","2023-01-22 21:55:00","Picking up where the last post left off — this time we're talking about the Dockerfile.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fdocker\u002Fstep-by-step-docker-dockerfile","3",{"title":6,"description":386},false,"en\u002FDocker\u002Fstep-by-step-docker-dockerfile",[384,397,398],"Step-by-Step Docker","Dockerfile",null,"2023-01-24 14:35:00","\u002Fen\u002Fdocker\u002F2023\u002F01\u002F22\u002Fstep-by-step-docker-dockerfile\u002F","zq5oDz_g0ul6gGyCkPolLa-fjzk1g_SDYErMx6MtlTA",{"newer":404,"older":408},{"url":405,"title":406,"date":407},"\u002Fen\u002Fdocker\u002F2023\u002F01\u002F23\u002Fstep-by-step-docker-hands-on\u002F","(3) Step-by-Step Docker — Hands-On Practice","2023-01-23 21:20:00",{"url":409,"title":410,"date":411},"\u002Fen\u002Fdocker\u002F2023\u002F01\u002F20\u002Fstep-by-step-docker-what-is-docker\u002F","(1) Step-by-Step Docker — What Is Docker?","2023-01-20 12:04:38",[413,418,423],{"url":414,"title":415,"date":416,"readingMinutes":417},"\u002Fen\u002Fdocker\u002F2024\u002F12\u002F19\u002Fdockerize-vite-vue-project\u002F","How to Dockerize a Vite + Vue Project","2024-12-19 16:36:18","2",{"url":419,"title":420,"date":421,"readingMinutes":422},"\u002Fen\u002Fdocker\u002F2023\u002F01\u002F29\u002Fstep-by-step-docker-table-of-contents\u002F","(11) Step-by-Step Docker — Table of Contents","2023-01-29 15:22:19","1",{"url":424,"title":425,"date":426,"readingMinutes":417},"\u002Fen\u002Fdocker\u002F2023\u002F01\u002F29\u002Fstep-by-step-docker-gui\u002F","(10) Step-by-Step Docker — Docker GUI","2023-01-29 15:20:19",1784020350735]